Conclusion
Hate bias crimes are widely acknowledged to be underreported, particularly among communities
that have lower trust in law enforcement, face language barriers, have experienced prior
discrimination by institutions, or fear retaliation, immigration consequences, or social stigma. The
bill’s provisions would support hate bias incident prevention and response, which has significant
equity implications. There is not sufficient data available to analyze the exact nature of the bill’s
impacts, but it is likely that the expanded definitions and reporting of the hate bias incidents under
HB 513/ Page 3

the bill will assist stakeholders and members of th e public in ascertaining a more complete picture
of how certain groups/identities are affected by hate bias in Maryland.
